    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3521622345" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3521622345" />
    <a title="Carrie (brightbeautifulthings)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9868179-carrie-brightbeautifulthings"><img alt="Carrie (brightbeautifulthings)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1491349112p2/9868179.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3521622345?book_show_action=true">Aug 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carrie (brightbeautifulthings)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carrie (brightbeautifulthings)" href="/user/show/9868179-carrie-brightbeautifulthings">Carrie (brightbeautifulthings)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9868179-carrie-brightbeautifulthings?shelf=summer-bingo-challenge-2020">summer-bingo-challenge-2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9868179-carrie-brightbeautifulthings?shelf=middle-grade">middle-grade</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9868179-carrie-brightbeautifulthings?shelf=illustrated">illustrated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9868179-carrie-brightbeautifulthings?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9868179-carrie-brightbeautifulthings?shelf=i-do-believe-in-spooks">i-do-believe-in-spooks</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9868179-carrie-brightbeautifulthings?shelf=story-collections">story-collections</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9868179-carrie-brightbeautifulthings?shelf=horrorshow">horrorshow</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3521622345" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12642651692681919703">When I was a kid, my older sister covered my window with a blanket and invaded the fort I had under my bed to scare the ever-loving shit out of me by reading stories from this book, and that’s the primary reason I haven’t read it until now. A peek at the table of contents shows it was actually More Scary Stories, since one of those tales in particular has lived on in my memory in vivid technicolor which, right there, shows the power and longevity of this collection. While its sway over adults is</span>
  <span id="freeText12642651692681919703" style="display:none">When I was a kid, my older sister covered my window with a blanket and invaded the fort I had under my bed to scare the ever-loving shit out of me by reading stories from this book, and that’s the primary reason I haven’t read it until now. A peek at the table of contents shows it was actually More Scary Stories, since one of those tales in particular has lived on in my memory in vivid technicolor which, right there, shows the power and longevity of this collection. While its sway over adults is questionable, it’s capable of utterly terrifying children, and if the stories aren’t enough, then Stephen Gammell’s absolutely gruesome black and white illustrations will do the trick. I find them way more disturbing than the stories and, much like the tales, once seen, they’ll never be forgotten.<br /><br />As an adult, the stories didn’t have the same power to keep me up late into the night listening for strange noises, but it has other things to hold adult interest, namely in the way that this collection came about. It’s a cool thing that Schwartz has done in collecting these tales, which were typically oral but widespread up until this point, and there are extended sections of notes and bibliography to credit his sources and direct readers to other versions of the tale–a scholar’s dream. I enjoyed the notes more than the stories, along with Schwartz’s theorizing on why we enjoy horror and why certain tales are so widespread. Some of them, like the first section, are obviously meant to be read aloud, preferably around a campfire.<br /><br />I’d also guess that there’s at least one story in here, if not several, that you’ve heard before because that’s the way that folktales and urban legends work. I was most familiar with the stories in Other Dangers: “The Hook”, “High Beams”, and “The Babysitter” (although that is a much milder version of The Hook Man than the one we told as teenagers), and I marveled a bit that their origins extend well before 1980; we’re still telling them, so they must have some power over us. “The Girl Who Stood On a Grave” is also familiar. Many of the stories are quick tales and not all that strong narratively (but, again, they’re meant to be told aloud, with a teller’s personal embellishments), but a handful of them still managed to give me a chill, with “The Guests” and “Room for One More” holding a special twist. Overall, it’s a lot of fun, and if you’re interested in oral storytelling traditions, folklore, or horror of any kind, it’s not to be missed.<br /><br />I review regularly at brightbeautifulthings.tumblr.com.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12642651692681919703" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


